# Task: Implement `apply_rule/2`

Implement the private `apply_rule/2` function — the rule dispatcher that takes a
single `value` and a `rule` and returns the anonymized value. It has one clause
per supported rule:

- `apply_rule(value, :redact)` — ignore the value and return the constant string
  `"[REDACTED]"`.
- `apply_rule(value, :hash)` — coerce the value to a string with `to_string/1`,
  compute its SHA-256 digest via `:crypto.hash(:sha256, ...)`, and return the
  digest as a **lowercase** hex string (use `Base.encode16(case: :lower)`).
- `apply_rule(value, :mask)` — coerce the value to a string and mask it by
  `String.length/1`: an empty string is returned unchanged; a 1-character string
  becomes `"*"`; a 2-character string is returned unchanged; any longer string
  keeps its first and last character and replaces every middle character with
  `*` (i.e. `first <> String.duplicate("*", len - 2) <> last`).
- `apply_rule(value, {:fake, seed})` — coerce the value to a string and delegate
  to `generate_fake/2`, passing the string value and the `seed`, so the same
  value/seed pair always yields the same deterministic fake.

Every clause must be a pure function of its inputs so that identical original
values map to identical anonymized outputs (referential integrity).

